[h1] one of the Best Games of it's Decade. [/h1]

A mix of all good elements that a action-like game have to have. Challenging, joyfull, rewarding and most of all: an epic experience.

Since the first boss you can feel how hard the game will be, however, it keeps getting more and more hard, but never let that be over the fun and enjoyment that each gunshot and "knockout" screen have. There is, for sure, other games like this around there, but i just cant think of another one doing difficulty and enjoyment being this close to eachother.

Above all the rage and maybe the quity ones, there is a beatifull game with such perfect details. The soundtrack looks like you are in fact in the 30's; and what can we say about a game that is totally painted, drawned and animated on paper? That's crazy, nothing more and nothing less

As i completed the game with all bosses on A or better rank, all i can say is: go for it.

!!FAIR FAIR FAIR!!

I love good challenge and I didn't know that some sort of "boss rush" games exists. So it is crazy that one of the best games ended up in my library as my virgin's first time. 

Bosses are about 2 minutes long on average if I remember correctly but it feels so LONG! This game is full of adrenaline, you keep shooting, you are doing your best and BAM next phase of boss that you do not know what to do because it's your first time and you have one last heart and oh my god your IRL heart is also pounding AF and you do not know which one you will lose first..

then after several attempts (20x 30sec runs) you start toying with loadouts. Yeah like "please somebody save me!" you keep rotating between the loadouts for another attempts (20x 1minute). You go back to your first loadout and after 3 attempts, you kill the boss.

"Okay, let's see the next one and quit the game.. Just see the next boss nothing more"

And you do well, you go to 50% of the level and the cycle continues until the CUPHEAD is full of your tears and you do not care about the bosses anymore and quit.

Then you start it up again after 10 minutes because YOU HAVE TO F KILL THE BOSS!!!

This game is FAIR! And this is the reason why some type of people just won't be able to put this game down for a long time (until they try DLC and back the F out as me and go back after half a year when their therapist said YOU CAN DO IT)

I can't stress this enough! this game is FAIR!! Not like Dark Souls and its "friendly trolling". Yeah it's fun to fall into dev's trap, but having a feeling of "ok I have to be careful because developer do not want to challenge me but just troll me" is too much.  Cuphead DLC has only one "trolly" thing but it was so cleverly done that I went from Happiness to shock to laughter to saying GOOD JOB loud for developers to hear.

Yes

Hit detection is Ice Spice level cheeks and the controls are unacceptably catatonic-state level unresponsive for such a fast paced jaunt. Janky self-sabotage super moves that push you back into danger and stop you from moving will make you wonder why they are even in the game.

Unlike other well known difficult titles that reward your persistence this is jumbled carnival sideshow nonsense, it isn't fun, only frustrating.

Don't be fooled by the art direction, people only beat this to brag about doing so, and post glowing reviews as a form of boosting ego afterwards.

I'll probably push through to the end to justify my wasted money, and boasting of my accomplishment like everyone else, but I will hate every moment of it and forever spark unnecessary arguments if Cuphead is ever a topic of positive discussion within earshot. 

4/10.

*EDIT*

Upon completion of this garbage, I find that only 16% of players have beaten it, are you kidding me? Page upon page of GLOWING reviews, yet these people put the controller down before they got halfway through the game. 

Don't believe the hype.

Cuphead and the DLC are phenomenal. Between Cupheads iconic and stunning art-style and fun challenging game-play little is left to be desired. Each boss is completely unique and interesting never being a chore to fight. I was expecting the game to be a bit harder just based on its difficulty being the main thing that is talked about however it really isn't that bad, challenging yes but most deaths will result from being surprised by a new attack. Once you know a bosses attack patterns it is pretty straightforward. It took me around 12 hours to clear the game and normally I would say that the price-tag doesn't match the playtime however Cuphead is a work of art, the animation behind this game alone is worth the price and I enjoyed every hour. Overall Cuphead and the DLC is stunningly beautiful and extremely fun to play.

Cuphead: A Masterpiece of Retro Gaming Revival

Cuphead isn't just a game; it's a meticulously crafted work of art that transports players into a mesmerizing world of 1930s animation and challenging gameplay. From its stunning hand-drawn visuals to its toe-tapping jazz soundtrack, every aspect of Cuphead exudes charm and creativity.

One of the first things that strikes you about Cuphead is its breathtaking art style. Every frame feels like it's been plucked straight from a classic cartoon, with vibrant colors, fluid animations, and expressive characters that burst with personality. It's a visual feast that pays homage to the golden age of animation while still feeling fresh and innovative.

But Cuphead isn't just about looks; it's also a test of skill and determination. The gameplay is tough but fair, with each boss battle presenting a unique challenge that will push you to your limits. Mastering the game's precise controls and learning the attack patterns of each boss is immensely satisfying, and the sense of accomplishment you feel after finally defeating a particularly tough opponent is second to none.

Beyond its challenging gameplay, Cuphead also boasts a killer soundtrack that perfectly complements the action on screen. From upbeat jazz tunes to haunting melodies, the music sets the mood for each encounter and adds another layer of depth to the overall experience.

But perhaps the most impressive thing about Cuphead is its attention to detail. From the smallest background elements to the elaborate boss designs, it's clear that a lot of love and care went into every aspect of the game's creation. It's the kind of game that invites you to explore every nook and cranny, uncovering hidden secrets and marveling at the craftsmanship on display.

In conclusion, Cuphead is a true masterpiece of game design that deserves all the praise it has received and more. With its stunning visuals, challenging gameplay, and infectious charm, it's a must-play experience for gamers of all ages. Whether you're a fan of classic animation or just love a good challenge, Cuphead is sure to delight and entertain from start to finish.

The first game I've ever bought on Steam (back in 2018), played it a little, then kept it in my library until a few weeks ago, for some reason. After six years of not playing it... 

[i]Oh boy, I LOVE it.[/i]

This game was crafted with love, and not a single soul can make me think otherwise. The characters are designed masterfully in such a way that I started wanting not to finish the game at some point near the ending.

Also, many define the game as quite hard, but if you have the patience -- and you're not insane enough [spoiler]like I am[/spoiler] to start a 100% achievement run, I'd say the game is not THAT hard and I really think it's balanced enough. 

I like games that kick the player in the ass often, that might be why I think that way, too, of course.

The gameplay variety (I believe there's [b]more than enough[/b] of it for a game of this length), the design choices, the easter eggs, the ~fire~ jazz soundtrack, the feeling of "'adult' game sugarcoated with goofy cartoony style" it gave me for some reason... Finishing this game gave me a partition of my old admiration for video games back to me.

As I'm commenting this, I'm pretty much in the beginning parts of the DLC (which a dear friend gifted me <:), I'm hoping it is as good as the main game, too, because I think the Netflix show (which is another part of the franchise established years after the release of the game) cannot even get near this game in many aspects. At least, that's what I saw from watching it partially.

Have a nice day, people, and thanks for checking my comment, even if you've read 4 words from it in total :D

My best friend and I played the hell out of this game a couple years back. We both would play for hours after school. He played Mugman and I was Cuphead. We were enamored by everything about this game, from the music to the amazing hand-drawn art. Our biggest triumph was beating Grim Matchstick after days and days of trying. We cheered so loud that his dad woke up and yelled at us. We didn't care though, we were riding the high of this game. Before we could beat the final boss, my friend passed away and he never got to see the end with me. I put the game down for a while, but I recently came back and beat the game just for him. Then I S-Ranked every single boss in his honor. Thank you Studio MDHR for the wonderful memories. This game will forever be a classic.

Cuphead is truly a once in a lifetime kind of game, its art style is absolutely gorgeous and its game-play is both satisfying and challenging to attempt over and over again. Each character and fight feels memorable, and the journey to beat the devil feels earned after all the trials and tribulations that the player goes through. Its soundtrack is also a bop to listen to, which always earns points.

Can't say I'm a big fan of the Run & Gun levels though; while they're still good, I found they don't ever really reach the highs that the boss fights do, and they kinda bring the game down a bit because you're really only going through them for the coins rather than the level itself. 

Ultimately though, Cuphead is a 9.5/10 for me, and is a thoroughly enjoyable experience for those who want challenge and don't give up easily!

I have finally finished both the main game and dlc after a total of 16.2 hours. Cuphead rocks big time. If you have never buy it or try it give it a go.

I actually purchased this game back in 2017 when it was launched. Tried playing it and realized that it was crazily tough and refunded the game. Fast forward to 2023, it was the annual Christmas sale and I decided to give it another go after playing another platformer Kaze and the wild masks. This time round Cuphead seems to be more manageable. I believed it was after having gone through the final lame boss of Kaze and the wild masks that the change happen. Try playing an easier platformer game before cuphead, it will help eases the transition into the game.

Cuphead is definitely a good buy if you want a challenge to your platformer game. It is crazily fun, very challenging and you are going to die God knows how many times. I died a total of 396 times before i completed both the main game and the dlc. 

With Cuphead, there will be time when you feel like breaking your controller. But if you stick to your gun with the game. Eventually you will kill the boss. Give it a shot especially if tough platformer game is your cup of tea. Just don't expect to breeze through the game. Definitely highly recommended for fans of platformer games with fantastic 1930s cartoony graphics. 

Just bear in mind, if you are going to buy cuphead. Buy it together with the dlc. Ms.Chalice do makes a big difference. So if mugman or cuphead is not your cup of tea. Try the playstyle of Ms.Chalice. God knows one of them might be the right fit for you.

PS : To be honest, i have always suck at platform games. So if i can finish cuphead and the dlc, so can you!

The visuals and music of this game are top notch. Studio MDHR absolutely NAILED the style they were going for.  On the gameplay side Cuphead is a very challenging game, and can be frustrating at times. However, the majority of the encounters are very well designed and I think there's only a few spots that maybe were a bit too hard at times, but I still pushed through. If you are looking for a polished and hard 2D action platforming shootemup game thing then look no further then Cuphead, its one of the best ever made.

Gorgeous animation, beautiful music and sound effects, and wonderfully clever design all around. Only a few BS moments here and there. Platforms and projectiles appearing off-screen, some attack combinations that are nigh-impossible to dodge, and often just too much happening on screen at once. But most of the time, everything is well telegraphed and usually errors are due to player skill. Lots of challenging and hidden content as well.

9/10 Nothing will do 30's animation, tone, and designs justice like this game does.

I'm afraid I don't understand the stellar reputation of this game at all, despite powering through completing it.

The difficulty this game is notorious for all to often comes from roadblock stages and bosses which contain patterns (see the cloud spawn patterns of the dragon boss as an example) in which random chance often leads to you being unable to avoid being hit. This game is very much style over substance in my experience. The art style is great, but there are only a handful of well designed boss fights.

Hit boxes are a discovery process, they are often nothing like the shape you would expect (a great example is stage 1 of the blue blob boss, in which it seems to be impossible to be hit by the boxing glove if you duck, even if the fist is covering almost your entire body).

The controls do not feel tight to me. I am a big fan of platformers and metroidvania style games, and either this game drops inputs like crazy, or the timings of parries (for example) are unintuitive. Either is bad. Speaking of unintuitive, I can't imagine playing this with the default control setup.

Run n' Gun stages are legitimately awful. There is not one Run n' Gun stage which even comes remotely close to being fun. Mercifully, these stages can be skipped if you don't mind not buying upgrades. Fortunately there are not many upgrades which are worth buying in my experience, as (for a casual player such as myself) the auto aim and shotgun guns were the only ones other than the regular gun I found useful, and the smoke bomb is the only upgrade I can even imagine using.

Cuphead is one tough nut to crack, no doubt about it! This game's got me duking it out with some serious challenges, but boy, it's one hell of a ride. The vintage cartoon vibes and those snazzy tunes, they've got this magic touch that keeps me grinning, even when I'm getting schooled left and right. I've danced with defeat more times than I can count, yet it's like a never-ending carnival of fun. No matter how many times I've bitten the dust, the charm of Cuphead still has me hooked. It's nothing short of swell.

But let me tip my admiration to those hard-working devs who went through the wringer to birth this masterpiece. I can't help but salute their sheer grit and gumption. Cuphead's visual pizzazz and tough-as-nails gameplay are a testament to the devs' dedication and artistic chops, earning them a truckload of respect from me. The blood, sweat, and tears poured into this indie gem by Studio MDHR shine through, turning it into not just a game but a love letter to the passion and skill of its creators.

If you haven't jumped into the Cuphead fray yet, I strongly reckon you give it a go. It's a real knockout; trust me, you're in for one hell of a time playing this game.

If your looking for a review on this game you've come to the wrong place, but if your looking for an outstanding pie recipe you've come to the right place.

Ingredients:
1. 6 tablespoons unsalted butter
2. 1/2 cup white sugar
3. 1/2 cup brown sugar
4. 1/4 cup water
5. 1/4 teaspoon cinnamon
6. 1 pinch salt
7. 5 apples - peeled, cored and sliced
8. 1 pastry for double-crust pie

Directions:
1. Preheat oven to 425 degrees F (220 degrees C).
2. Combine butter, white sugar, brown sugar, water, cinnamon, and salt in a saucepan over medium heat. Bring to a boil, remove from heat and set aside.
3. Roll out half the pastry to fit a 9-inch pie plate. Place bottom crust in pie plate; pour in apple slices.
4. Roll out top crust into a 10-inch circle. Cut into 8 (1-inch) wide strips with a sharp paring knife or pastry wheel. Weave the pastry strips, one at a time, into a lattice pattern. Fold the ends of the lattice strips under the edge of the bottom crust and crimp to seal.
5. Pour butter-sugar mixture over top of pie, coating the lattice, and allowing any remaining sauce to drizzle through the crust.
6. Bake in the preheated oven for 15 minutes. Reduce heat to 350 degrees F (175 degrees C), and bake until the crust is golden brown, the caramel on the top crust is set, and the apple filling is bubbling, 35 to 40 more minutes. Allow to cool completely before slicing.

Review of the game "Cuphead" - a masterpiece among games!
First of all, I want to point out that I spent a whopping 165 hours in this game, learning every mechanic and achieving every achievement. And I couldn't be more enthusiastic about everything that "Cuphead" represents.
The developers of this game simply did a great job with every detail. Their dedication and creativity shows in every texture and every unique character animation. They spent many years creating a universe that truly lives and breathes its own rules.
Not only the visual aspects of the game are admirable, but the musical accompaniment is so high quality and beautiful that it is simply amazing. Gorgeous melodies that fully match the atmosphere and action on the screen, create a unique atmosphere and add depth to the gameplay.
And what’s even more amazing is that the developers didn’t limit themselves to just the original game, but released an update in the form of additional content. New bosses, a compelling story, and other improvements that rival the quality of the original game show that the development team truly cares about its players.
I especially want to note that the game "Cuphead" was so successful that Netflix released an animated series based on this game. This is another indicator of how "Cuphead" has become a true cult phenomenon and will find its fans not only among gamers, but also among the general public.
Overall, Cuphead is a game that is simply breathtaking. It combines stunning graphics, mesmerizing music, addictive gameplay and an endless number of levels where every obstacle you overcome brings incredible satisfaction.
If you want to be completely immersed in a unique gaming world, feel the drive and experience real pleasure from the game, then "Cuphead" is exactly what you need. Prepare for a fabulous adventure that will captivate you from the first minutes and won't let you go until the very end!

Game play: The game play is simple, yet engaging. The controls are tight knit, easy to grasp, and work very well. I have zero complaints.
    The loading times are barely noticeable. You can boot it up and play within thirty seconds.
    The bosses are amazing. The ground bosses are easily the best. the aerial bosses are great as well, but you lose a lot of the choice in what weapons you can use. There are also some other challenges that you can play to get new weapons/charms. The run'n'guns are definitely the weakest of the bunch, but they get better as you get further into the game. There are also the mausoleums, which are short parrying challenges, that you play to unlock "super arts", but there aren't many of them and they're pretty repetitive.
    Aside from the levels, there's also a world map to explore during your down time with characters to talk to and a few side quests here and there. I only wish there was more.
    Though the weapons are well balanced, the charms (buffs and abilities) could use some equalling out. Half of them are what I'd call training wheels. They're nice when you're starting out, but once you're good enough at it, they're not worth the charm slot. And some of them become practically useless in the aerial bosses. The "whetstone" charm represents the huge missed potential of them.
    The final boss fight of the game though decently difficult, isn't anything particularly hard compared to any other boss in the game.
    I hear people complain about the RNG, but I don't think much control is taken away from the player.
    If you're not able to keep at something until you get it then this game isn't for you.

Visuals & Audio: Inspired by 1930's rubber hose animation, the graphics in this game are beautiful. I can't say anything that hasn't already been said.
    All the characters speak in speech boxes, so there isn't much more than some grunts and other sounds. The music is where the audio truly shines. Again I can't say much that hasn't already been said. The soundtrack is just spectacular.

Story: The story is simple, but charming, which fits with the over all theme of the game.

Final review: After 100% completing this game, I have concluded that it is a flawed, but lovingly crafted, masterpiece that takes time and practise to master. Studio MDHR put their heart and soul into this game.

Game play: 4.5/5
Visuals & Audio: 5/5
Difficulty: 3.5/5

Total score: 4.5/5

A masterpiece!

Pros:
+ Simple to pick up, difficult to master.
+ Nostalgic art style inspired by cartoons of the 30s. For those who are into Cuphead's art design, there is an official art book named The Art of Cuphead which is absolutely gorgeous and a must-have.
+ Great animation details. (However, you won't be able to pay much attention to them since you will be too occupied by the bosses!)
+ Great variety of level design: the bosses, their patterns/moves, etc. Just never feel repetitive.
+ Jazz soundtrack (3 hours of original recordings, wow!) also à la 30s, which is really rare these days.
+ Sweet visual and auditory bonuses. For visuals, you can [spoiler]unlock the 2-stripe and the black-and-white filter[/spoiler]. For sounds, you can [spoiler]choose between big bang or piano solo for the map background music[/spoiler], and you can also [spoiler]unlock a vintage filter, which makes the music sound like coming from a gramophone[/spoiler].
+ Upon beating the game, Expert Mode unlocks, reserved for those who think this game is not challenging enough.
+ If even Expert Mode is not hardcore enough for you, there is a local co-op mode for two players (needs at least one controller). You and your friend can fight hand in hand against bosses that have double health!
+++++++ Great plot: [spoiler]Having gambling issues, you, Cuphead, have lost all your money in a casino. Now you owe your soul to the devil, and you have no choice but become his debt collector. So you beat up every other deadbeat on the isle. On a whim, you also beat up the honest casino owner and even the devil himself. Thanks to you, debts are forgiven, and all deadbeats live happily ever after.[/spoiler]

Cons:
Not that I can think of. However, just a little caveat for casual players: this game is hard. Like, really HARD. As an average player, I have died 500 times during my first playthrough which lasts around 15 hours. However, most levels last less than 2 minutes, so you don't lose much dying. Just press on, practise more, and you will steadily progress through the game.

Verdict:
Absolutely recommend. It is such a pleasure to look at the animation of this game and to listen to its Jazz soundtrack. You surely shouldn't be daunted by its difficulty and deprive yourself of this unique experience!

Edited:

I love this game. Its difficulty can be challenging at times but its still very fun. The art style is very charming and looks great. There is quite a bit more content after completing the main game. For example expert mode which adds more hp to bosses. The difficulty definitely ramps up after the first 2 bosses and the first run and gun which are more tutorials than anything. The DLC provides a couple more weapons, charms and Mrs Chalice along with 6 more bosses and a gauntlet however it doesn't add any more run and guns.

If your looking for a challenging but fun game I would definitely recommend Cuphead as well as the DLC too go along with it, its definitely worth it in my opinion. Anyone who is fairly familiar with video games should be able too beat this games main story. I would recommend using a controller ( like an xbox controller ) instead of a keyboard. Its worth all the money down too the coin in my opinion. Fun game play and a brilliant art style combine too make in my opinion one of the best indie games and also one of the best games too be sold on steam. If you some spare money give Cuphead a shot.

At its core, Cuphead is a boss rush game. You travel to thematically distinct regions to battle creatively designed bosses which all have their own unique mechanics. Fights are connected via a top down hub world (similar to Donkey Kong Country 3) in which you meet oddball characters and discover hidden secrets. 

The visuals and sound design blend together to improve the game’s flow and sell the old school animation style. The jazzy soundtrack guides the gameplay into feeling quick and bouncy. The juxtaposition between the hand drawn foreground and watercolor background allow the levels to be incredibly detailed without distracting from stage hazards and intractable objects. 

I wouldn’t consider Cuphead to be an “easy” game, but I would argue that it is not as difficult as it’s made out to be. Most bosses can be beaten within 3 to 4 minutes, so the penalty for dying is more of less nonexistent. Rather than relying on quick reflexes to beat levels, you can progress through the entire game just be familiarizing yourself with the enemy attack patterns. And if a boss phase feel too unforgiving you can customize your build to accommodate for a different play style.

Cuphead is an absolutely amazing game. The soundtrack, art style and gameplay make the game great. It is quite hard, lots of trial and error should be expected. However, every loss feels like you have just made some progress. It never quite feels frustrating. If you like tough games, especially platformers in the fashion of Celeste or Super Meat Boy, you are likely to love Cuphead. Even someone who doesn't enjoy the genre so much, or gets frustrated easily, would probably find the game amusing. It is specifically centered around boss battles, so you can expect lots of that, as well as a few actual standard platforming levels. This is the definition of a game that is easy to learn, hard to master, and even harder to fully complete.

I found the game amazing, and I managed to do everything, even the DLC and expert mode. Overall, Cuphead is a nice, enjoyable game that I would recommend to nearly anyone. 9.5/10

Cuphead is a incredibly iconic game that is brought up time and time again, I started playing it around 5 years ago on Xbox and since then have bought it on switch and now steam. It is a brutal game that is satisfying to conquer and is very fun to play. I would recommend anyone to play it Cup head is worth the money 100%

   Cuphead's unique art and visual style sets it apart from other shoot'em ups and platformers. It has a stunning 1930's cartoon style and is completely hand drawn. The game also makes use of watercolor backgrounds clay models and a in studio symphony to create a perfect atmosphere of music and visuals.
  
   The game itself is very hard but after some time and a few playthroughs you can learn the rhythm of the bosses and it becomes much easier. I personally have beaten cuphead probably 50+ times, it works well as a co-op game with friends. As much as I love cuphead one drawback about the game play is that some bosses attacks just don't really work right in multiplayer particularly homing attacks become completely unfair as they just randomly lock on to a player so you cant know its coming for you.

   The game has a wide variety of weapons charms and supers to mix up the game play and let you create the perfect load out to suit your play style or to body a boss. For the most part no weapon is objectively better than any other giving the player lots of options for their load out. The charms are balanced well also however at least for me and people I've played the game with the supers aren't balanced well with the first one being far and away the best.

    The boss fights in the game are impeccable, instead of having a series of levels before a boss fight Cuphead opts for non stop boss fights with the occasional mausoleum or run in gun. The bosses are fast paced and brutally hard, however if you can learn the fights it becomes super fun to fight them being able to quickly take them down without to much trouble. Cuphead works very well for challenge runs by restricting load out options for this very reason as it lets you truly put your knowledge of the bosses to the test.

   Cupheads DLC is also worth buying it adds a whole new isle with new bosses and a parry themed gauntlet the new bosses are harder than old ones but follow any thing stated before. The main drawback to the DLC is that the new weapons are somewhat unbalanced especially compared to the old balancing of weapons crack shot is well cracked making several shots obsolete.

    100% this game drove me crazy in particular S-ranking all the DLC bosses but it was worth it and I would still replay cuphead any day. It is definitely worth buying for it stunning visuals, amazing music and great game play. Cuphead is an easy 10/10

The game is great. The difficulty level is very on point in such a manner that the game doesn't feel infuriating or too easy, even though the simple mode exists, which I guess is for the casual gamer, the game doesn't feel too difficult at any point.

Sure, you can go and 200% the game, beating every boss with S rank which is quite difficult, considering there is the junkyard robot which would be the worst thing imaginable, but that feels dreadful and non-rewarding.

Cuphead is a fantastic platforming boss rush game and you should buy it. 

Though i feel like i really need to highlight something that ive noticed while playing.

Every now and then bosses seem to sometimes dish out RNG attacks at you, which artificially increases difficulty. 

While there obviously are attack patterns for each boss and memorizing them certainly helps, every now and then you'll scratch your head wondering why the boss did some attacks twice or even something completely different at that point in your run, which really just ends up feeling cheap and unfair towards the player. 

Again, after many hours i am quite confident in saying that it really does the aforementioned every now and then, just to give you a hard time.

It's BS but im willing to look past that because i love the unique art style and i appreciate the amount of effort and dedication that went into the game.

One of the most memorable, challenging, and fun games I've ever played in my life. I must stress that I was 100% keen for this game for a long time. However, I was never going to buy it if it had that rotten Denuvo crap, which is the devil's stinky excrement. Luckily, it doesn't!!!

The game itself is grueling, but in the most delightful way. You will die many, many times. But if you're like me, you will find this entertaining. You will see some people complaining that it's to hard; I don't like this criticism!! 

It's sad when Devs buckle under preassure from your Candy Crush sookie la-la type panzies asking to make the game a walk in the park. Brigador faced a lot of criticism for the game being to hard, now it's so ridiculously easy, it's not really fun. But Cuphead did not buckle under any talk of it being too hard, which is great! It's actually not really [i]that[/i] hard, it just requires patience, but this trait is lacking in dimwitted people who want things quick and easy. At the end of the day, the difficulty of the game has been designed masterfully.

The graphics are amazing. There's no other game that does what this game does graphically. I don't know why Disney isn't paying the devs $10 Billion to work on some games using a similar animation style. 

Overall, I wholeheartedly recommend this game at full price!! The Delicious Last Course, exceeded all my expectations, this game is one of the greatest ever made :cuphead:

This game is not only beautifully drawn with excellent sound effects and music, but it plays very well too. The controls are tight and Cuphead is very responsive to inputs. I press on the jump button, he jumps. There is no input delay what-so-ever. The level design is creative and thanks to the colorful art, is more memorable.

Cuphead is split into 3 worlds that get progressively harder (or 4 if you buy the dlc), but there's a catch: This game is also quite tough starting in the very first world, which is not necessarily everyone's cup of tea, but I like it this way. I don't think the base game is too hard either. Now, trying to obtain every collectable and maxing out the rank of every level, that's a whole other story.

If you have never played an action game, let alone a sidescroller, before or you have some sort of disability, (since the game requires high reflexes and attention) I can't really recommend it to you, but in general the game is fantastic and is worth every cent from my own personal experience. I otherwise recommend it to everyone else to at least give it a try.

[b]Review:[/b] Cuphead, what a game that manages to impress me in every way. This is far from one of the best games I've played in my life, literally everything in this game is amazing. I can't think of a single flaw that destroyed my experience with it. Because this game has a lot of replay value, in which you learn the boss and approach said boss in the most optimal way you can. [b]Price:[/b] Sure it may be way too pricey but for the sheer amount of effort and care put into this game, it's definitely worth buying.

[b]Rating:[/b] 9.8/10

Cuphead is a game that certainly deserves the "Game of the Year" award at the "Favorite Child" award. There are several key aspects to this game that make it unique and outstanding.

Firstly, Cuphead has a unique visual style that certainly attracts attention. The graphic design of the game is completely inspired by the classic American animated films of the 1930s, created manually using the techniques of cartoon animation of that time. This creates a unique atmosphere and a feeling as if you are playing a cartoon. High-quality animation and detailed characters and levels raise the bar for visual performance to a new level.

Secondly, the game offers insanely complex gameplay that requires skill, reaction and strategic thinking from the player. Cuphead is a classic platformer with elements of "bitmap", where players have to go through a series of difficult bosses, battles with which require high speed, accuracy and memorization of enemy attacks. However, even despite its complexity, the game remains fair, giving players a sense of satisfaction and achievement at the levels passed.

In addition, the game offers a great soundtrack that perfectly matches the visual style and gameplay. Music in the game is a characteristic feature of each level and boss, and it helps to create an atmosphere of trial and tension. The soundtrack, recognized by experts and players, allows you to fully immerse yourself in the game world of Cuphead.

Finally, the game also has a great co-op mode that allows you to play with a friend or family member on the same screen. This is a great opportunity to spend time having fun and intense, along with the possibility of solving complex tasks and challenges together.

Summing up all these aspects, Cuphead stands out significantly among other games and deserves the "Game of the Year" award at the "Favorite Child" award. It offers a memorable visual style, challenging and addictive gameplay, a great soundtrack and the opportunity to play with friends or family. Cuphead is a game that is not only technically outstanding, but also leaves the feeling of a true work of art in the world of video games.

Obviously, the biggest draw here is the presentation. I don't want to know how much time and pain it took to hand-craft every one of the incredible animations in the game. The high difficulty of the bosses give you the chance to digest and scrutinize every animations and appreciate how well they telegraph attacks. The animations are so over-the-top, and you'll never expect what these 3 to 5 phase bosses have in store for you. The OST is also one of my favorites in video games, a ragtime jazz ensemble that nails the aesthetic and just sounds awesome. Boss fights are usually about 2-3min long, and each track is nearly 5 min. That's how much extra effort they put into the music.

You'd think a game with such a high focus on artistry may falter in the gameplay department, but holy hell, this game is a blast to play. The general concept of the bosses and levels is they have a set of moves that are simple to avoid, but what makes it so challenging, fun, and exciting is how all these moves layer on top of each other during the fight in creative ways. For example, one boss has a rollercoaster cart that appears in the background before running across the screen as an attack. You have to keep track of the cart and dodge the boss, who launches balloon dogs at you. It's all crafted in a way that is difficult but not unfair, and its so rewarding and enjoyable to dissect and manage all the things on the screen going on at once. 

And get the DLC, if you don't, shame on you.

[h1] Ana oyunu bitirdim ve daha herşey taze iken yorumlarımı yazmak istiyorum. [/h1]

Öncelikle oyun harika. Çizimleriyle, müzikleriyle, atmosferiyle, yaratıcığıyla tamamen mükemmel. Nadiren gelen mücevher oyunlardan birisi.Oyunun sadece bir sıkıntısı var, o da zorluk dengesi. Bakın tekrar ediyorum, oyunun zorluğu değil, zorluğun dengesi. Şu kısımda detayları var isterseniz diğer satıra atlayabilirsiniz.

[spoiler] İlk olarak oyunda 3 ada var ve her adada bosslarla dövüşüyor ve en sonunda şeytanla yüzleşiyorsunuz. Oyuncu ilerledikçe ordan burdan topladığı parayla ekipmanlarını geliştirebiliyor ve açık ara bazı ekipmanlar sizin favorileriniz oluyor çünkü ciddi manada güçlüler. Mesela ben bosslar ufak şeyler yolladığında crackshot silahı, kendisi geldiğinde charge silahı kullanırım. Bu kombo ile yapamayacağınız şey yok. Bu demek ki ilerledikçe düşmanlar daha zor olmalı ama maalesef pek öyle işlemiyor.
İlk adada Hilda Berg korkunç derecede zor bi boss. Oyunda uçak kullanmayı ilk öğrendiğimiz bossun hilda berg olması çok yanlış bir seçim. Aşırı fazla dikkat dağıtıcı etken var ve yeni oyuncuların çoğunun tıkandığı yer orası. Ondan sonra ikinci adada gelen Djimmi the Great (Alaadin kılıklı adam) ondan çok daha kolay bir boss. Aynı durum da Ribby and Croaks'da geçerli. İkinci Baroness Von Bon Bon bile bu kurbağalardan çok daha kolay.
Üçüncü adada Dr. Kahl's Robot'u var. Allahın belası boss. Geçtim ama tamamen tesadüfen geçtim. İlk aşaması korkunç uzun sürüyor ve bu da sadece ilk kısmı geçmeyi bile imkansız kılıyor. Ama şöyle bir durum var ki ikinci ve üçüncü aşaması aşırı kolay. Tüm oyun boyunca en zorlandığım kısım bu bossun ilk kısmı oldu.
Tl;Dr İlk karşımıza çıkan bosslar sonradan gelen bosslardan daha zor olabiliyor, bazen de tersine 2 ve 3. adadaki boss anormal derecede kolay olabiliyor. [/spoiler]



İkinci zorluk problemi kesinlikle final. King Dice boss tasarımı berbat. Sizden zar atmanızı istiyor ve bu zara gelen boss ile savaşıyorsunuz. Mevzu şu ki 1,6 ve 9. boss tamamen canınızı yemek için tasarlanmış. Oyunda rastgele bu 9 bossun üçüne ekstra can atıyor ve oyunu resetleyip o kalplerin saydığım üç boss dışında bir bossun üstüne gelene kadar restart atıyorsunuz. Eğer iyi bir şeye denk gelirse kalperin hepsini toplayın çünkü şanslı değilseniz ihtiyacınız olacak. Bitirdiğiniz vakit king dice parmaklarıyla %50 şans ihtimaliyle sağdan veya soldan kart atmaya başlayacak. Bunları parrylemek korkunç derecede zor bu yüzden çoğu kişi benim yaptığım gibi en sağa veya en sola gidiyor. Orda durduğunuz sürece %50 şansla kurtuluyorsunuz. O kartları sizin ters tarafınıza yollarken siz zıplayıp saldıracaksınız. Bu kadar basit. Şansınız yoksa her seferinde kartlar size gelecek. King Dice'ı bir şekilde yenince karşınıza şeytan geliyor ve şunu söylemem gerekiyor ki şeytan fazlasıyla kolaydı. King dice'a saatlerimi gömdüm, robot bossu da aynı şekilde. Ama şeytan çok tahmin edilebilir basit saldırılara sahipti. Bu kadar kolay olacağını düşünmemiştim ve bu kolaylık beni tatmin etmedi doğrusu.

Bunlar mırın kırınlar tabiki. Oyun mükemmel. Kesinlikle alın oynayın.

The most important thing that makes Cuphead special is its unique art design, which is extremely rare in video games. The cartoons of the 1930s are the inspiration for this artistic design, which is both simple and beautiful just like them. This rare beauty is mixed with a simple and smooth gameplay that makes defeating the bosses a very special feeling of triumph; A victory that can only be achieved by putting in effort and precision. Although Cuphead is only an hour long, the game's difficulty ensures that it takes more than eight hours to finish the game; And this is not a problem because difficulty never gets monotonous and boring. Also, apart from the visual beauty of Cuphead, classical music is another reason that makes Cuphead an exciting and enjoyable game.
+:
Beautiful art design like 1930s animations, both characters and environments
A simple, exciting and challenging gameplay that is never gets repetitious
Fantastic design of boss fights
Run 'n Gun stages that diversify the gameplay
Beautiful and audible classical musics
Interesting comedy that runs in the blood of the game
Very good audio design

Cuphead, developed by StudioMDHR, is a visually stunning and challenging run-and-gun game that pays homage to the classic cartoons of the 1930s. Released in 2017, Cuphead captivated players with its unique art style, captivating soundtrack, and intense gameplay. In this review, we'll explore the key elements that make Cuphead a true artistic masterpiece and an unforgettable gaming experience.

Artistic and Visual Splendor:
Cuphead's hand-drawn art style is a true testament to the dedication and craftsmanship of its developers. Inspired by the animation styles of the 1930s, the game's visuals are a nostalgic throwback to the golden era of cartoons. Every frame is meticulously designed, with vibrant colors, fluid animations, and attention to detail that brings the game world to life. Cuphead's visual splendor is a feast for the eyes and a true work of art.

Immersive and Nostalgic Soundtrack:
The game's soundtrack, composed by Kristofer Maddigan, perfectly complements the visual style and enhances the overall experience. The jazzy, big band-inspired music transports players back to the era of classic cartoons, further immersing them in the game's world. The lively and energetic tunes add an extra layer of excitement and nostalgia, making every boss battle and level feel like a thrilling adventure.

Challenging Gameplay and Precision:
Cuphead is renowned for its challenging gameplay that requires precision, timing, and quick reflexes. The game is filled with intense boss battles and platforming levels that test the player's skills and patience. Each encounter presents unique patterns and mechanics that need to be mastered in order to progress. While the difficulty can be daunting at times, the sense of accomplishment upon overcoming a challenge is immensely rewarding.

Cooperative Multiplayer:
Cuphead features cooperative multiplayer, allowing players to team up with a friend and tackle the game's challenges together. The cooperative mode adds a new dimension to the gameplay, requiring communication and coordination between players. It's an excellent addition that fosters a sense of camaraderie and shared triumph as you work together to conquer the game's toughest obstacles.

This game is unique.

PROS:
 - Unique visual style (hand-drawn) and music (jazz).
 - No bugs.
 - Good and fun game, some bosses (about 4-5) are really cool.
 - Local Co-op.
 - Really low requirements (I can run it on my work laptop).

CONS:
 - Short (8-9h for the average Joe). No replayability.
 - Too difficult to play co-op with casual gamers.
 - RNG bullshit (winning should depend on skill, not luck).
 - Parry needs refining (I keep feeling cheated when timing the parry and still getting hit).
 - Things that spawn and are currently out of screen hit you if you're also out of screen (this adds to RNG bullshit, if I NEED to be there because of RNG, why do I have to randomly get hit?).
 - NO online co-op (In 2020? Seriously?)

All in all, it has 19 bosses (4-5 really cool, 3-4 are bullshit), 6 platforming levels and requires a good deal of pacience and luck (some bosses take about 20-30 tries). 

Content ain't worth the 20 euro asking price, when Hollow Knight exists. Shame.

[h1] The Good [/h1]
• [u]Art and Animation[/u]: Cuphead boasts a visually stunning hand-drawn art style inspired by 1930s cartoons, creating a unique and charming aesthetic. The animation is fluid and brings the characters to life in a captivating way.

• [u]Innovative Boss Battles[/u]: The game features creatively designed and challenging boss battles that showcase a variety of patterns and phases. Each encounter feels distinct, offering a fresh and engaging experience throughout the game.

• [u]Jazzy Soundtrack[/u]: Cuphead's soundtrack is a standout feature, featuring an original jazzy and big band composition that perfectly complements the game's visual style. The music enhances the overall atmosphere and adds to the retro feel.

• [u]Cooperative Gameplay[/u]: Cuphead supports local cooperative play, allowing two players to team up and tackle the challenging levels together. The cooperative mode adds a layer of strategy and coordination, enhancing the overall fun.

• [u]Attention to Detail[/u]: The game pays meticulous attention to detail, capturing the essence of classic animation and creating a cohesive world filled with imaginative characters, environments, and subtle nods to pop culture.

• [u]Fair Difficulty Curve[/u]: While challenging, Cuphead maintains a fair difficulty curve. The game gradually introduces new mechanics and boss patterns, giving players the opportunity to learn and adapt without becoming overly frustrating.

[hr][/hr]

[h1] The Bad [/h1]
• [u]High Difficulty Level[/u]: While the difficulty curve is fair, Cuphead is known for its high level of difficulty, which may be a deterrent for some players looking for a more casual gaming experience.

• [u]Limited Exploration[/u]: Cuphead primarily focuses on boss battles and run-and-gun levels, limiting the exploration aspect. Players looking for a more expansive world with exploration elements may find the game somewhat restrictive.

• [u]No Level Variety[/u]: The levels, while visually distinct, often follow a similar structure of boss battles or run-and-gun sequences. Some players may desire more variety in level design and objectives.

[hr][/hr]

[h1] The Ugly [/h1]
• [u]Repetitiveness for Solo Players[/u]: Solo players may find certain boss battles repetitive, as the game's true charm often shines in cooperative play. The experience might feel less dynamic and varied when played alone.

• [u]Occasional Hitbox Issues[/u]: Some players have reported occasional hitbox issues, where it seems like they should avoid an attack, but they still get hit. These instances can be frustrating, particularly during challenging boss encounters.

• [u]Limited Replayability[/u]: Once players complete the main campaign, Cuphead's replayability may be limited for some, as the primary focus is on mastering boss battles. Additional modes and content updates could enhance long-term appeal.

[hr][/hr]

Forgot to add a review so here it is now. The game is certainly a amazing game for both single player and multiplayer with friends. Luckily Steam allows for remote play or this game would be a lot less fun for me. 9.5/10
**Positives**
-Difficult at first but becomes easy once mastered. When starting the game there will be MANY frustrating moments that feel out of the player control but each fight is premade so the more runs you play the easier it becomes. If you cannot handle losing a few hundred times then this game will not be for you. 
-With friends the bosses gain a bit more HP but the attack patterns are the same as single player. Allowed with infinite revives as long as both players are able to parry each other's ghost. If you are very experience in the game then you can bring a friend and constantly revive them while they scream "please stop let me die". The most memorable moment for me and hopefully for many. 
-Fun+All different abilities/powers allows the player to cater toward their specific playstyle.
**Neutral**
-Run and Gun sections is my least favorite part of the game. Some will enjoy this mode but for me I love boss rush type games more than platforming. 
-No punishment for losing. There is no insensitive to not constantly run your head into a boss until you randomly win. 
**Bad**
-Many of the abilities and weapons are clearly outclassed. The balance could use some work in my opinion.
-The difficulty increase in the game is somewhat artificial as there will be slight changes to the boss attacks such as, more projectiles, faster movement, etc... it's ultimately the same boss with the same attack pattern with the same playstyle. Better than 99% of other games that only increase dmg and hp but still disappointing for this game.
-Low Replay value. There will be no new content and no reason to start a new save unless you want S+ and P ranks that won't affect the game.

This is the most beautifully aesthetic video game ever made, and I will stick by that statement unironically. Nothing can ever compete with the dedicated craftmanship that went into each and every frame, which btw was hand drawn and hand inked before being scanned into the computer. Regardless of the rest of the game, the visual spectacle alone is worth twice the money. 

The game is known for being brutally difficult, but not in a punishing way. No significant progress is ever lost (except fighting King Dice at the very end). Also, the game does very well at feeling like it is beatable, and every boss can be overcome with enough sheer patience and practice. 

The difficulty is a significant downside for me, however. I was forced to use a mod to artificially change the game's difficulty, even beyond Simple mode, to the point that it felt more enjoyable for me. 

The default control scheme is also fairly horrendous. Changing controls on PC is an absolute necessity, as nothing is mapped in any intuitive way. Also forces use of the keyboard for everything, never using the mouse at all. Probably this is because the game was made for Xbox and haphazardly ported over to PC, but still... could have used some more forethought. Some keyboards have built in fail safes that prevent too many keys to be pressed at once... which becomes a serious issue with some bosses.

You'll start with the art direction. "Ooh, look at that! It's classic rubberhose animation. Isn't that fun?" You decide to check it out.

To your surprise, it's a run-and-gun boss-battle game! The animation helps sell the bosses' movement and helps you predict what they're going to do. "Wow, this is so much fun!" You fight the vegetables, do the first run-and-gun stage, everything's great.

And then somewhere along the way, it'll hit you.

This game is hard. REALLY hard. This game will destroy you frontways and back. It won't be the same bosses as everyone else--maybe you'll beat a boss in a half-dozen tries that took your friend scores of attempts--but somewhere along the way, you'll hit a hard boss, and then you'll realize this is just Island 1, and there's still two more to go. XD

But don't let the difficulty hold you back! Once you get to the end, lose to the Devil fifty times, and then FINALLY kick his kiester, you'll feel like a god among mortals. And then you'll boot up the DLC (Delicious Last Course) and get your butt kicked one thousand times again.

A Vintage Delight Filled with Modern Challenge

⭐️⭐️⭐️⭐️⭐

From the very first glance, "Cuphead" captures the essence of a bygone era, presenting itself with the allure and charm of a 1930s cartoon. But don't let its vintage appearance deceive you – this is a game that demands precision, patience, and perseverance.

The art style is breathtaking. It's clear that the developers, Studio MDHR, poured immense love and dedication into recreating the look and feel of old-school animations. Every frame of the game feels like a moving work of art, with intricate details and fluid animations that are a treat to the eyes. Complementing the visual treat is the jazzy, upbeat soundtrack that sets the perfect tone for Cuphead's adventures.

Gameplay-wise, "Cuphead" is no walk in the park. It's a challenging run-and-gun platformer that demands quick reflexes and a sharp eye. The boss battles, which are the highlight of the game, are varied and require players to learn patterns and tells to come out victorious. This might not appeal to everyone, especially those easily frustrated, but for those who appreciate a challenge, it's immensely rewarding.

Co-op mode brings another layer of fun and chaos, allowing a second player to join as Mugman. The cooperative gameplay does not necessarily make the game easier, but it offers a different dynamic that can be a lot of fun with the right partner.

A few minor gripes include occasional difficulty spikes and the desire for even more content. But these are small criticisms in an otherwise masterful game.

In conclusion, "Cuphead" is a masterpiece that bridges the gap between the past and present. It's a loving tribute to 1930s animation and old-school gaming challenges. It might test your patience at times, but the satisfaction of overcoming its trials is worth every ounce of effort.

You've likely heard about it and likely know what to expect but to reiterate: This is mostly a boss rush and often a bullet hell as well so when deciding whether to take up the challenge do consider are you ok with both as all Plane and DLC levels are going to be like that.

Disclaimers aside this is a very solid title for what it aims for. Nothing I could say will be anything new or unsaid considering its popularity and ratings but there is always some room to praise the craftsmanship of the old-school, hand-made animations and graphics. The game itself doesn't stay behind - bosses are varied, cartoonishly goofy and very difficult. I was very pleased to see how well balanced it is, that is I could almost never say that something happened and it wasn't my fault or my lack of positional awareness...though guess I could complain about sometimes way too much on the screen but apparently bullet hell is part of its design especially with the DLC now being out. But in short - game is refined well enough that skill issue is more often the actual problem than the game itself. Which is excellent, wish more games had this level of polish...but then considering I failed to beat it makes me feel very old ^^"
Not that there aren't ways to make it easier as there is "simple" mode and game genie to boost our HP (although that trick seems nigh impossible to do on keyboard) buuut it cripples the end score (and achievement possibilities as consequence) which thus seems to defeat the purpose as challenge is all the game is about. There isn't much reason to cheese a boss this way as there isn't much story to pursue - there is only as much of it to justify some boss rush so it's not like there is some epic story to conclude. It's simply the skill galore thus if someone's not up for the challenge then there isn't much reason to get the game.
I did take it to try to Complete it to see do I still "got it" [strike]but I guess I don't...I mean I probably could if I grinded harder against my better judgement but I also can acknowledge my limits and pursue something else instead. It sounds wise but sure makes me feel so old, but then sacrifice for bragging rights is a poor deal ^^". But babbling of some wimp aside - [/strike]
[strike]Edit: I did beat it all on A rank in the end after a longer break, not all-achievements kind of thing but done most.[/strike] Edit2: Nevermind, got them all. After a time I don't think it was a matter of "still having it" but pushing myself into a genre/playstyle I never liked/been good at in the first place and there is no point pushing a challenge of which structure and principles I dislike.
Anyways if you pick this is up just remember to take breaks and know when to stop. Playing tilted is never healthy and may lead to both anger or depression and make you write gibberish philosophy like I did here before editing it... But yeah if it's too hard no shame in dropping it and it's nobody's business if you do. It may just be not quite your cup of tea and you don't realize it like I didn't for 20 hours.

This is a game that you owe yourself playing if you enjoy difficult titles or platforms. What an absolute achievement. Incredibly unique and inspired artstyle that is pulled off in every corner, relatively short, but with a crap ton of content at the same time. This game is the Dark Souls of cup-based rubber-hose inspired platformers. It really makes you feel like a cup. Seriously though, it really is on the same level as Dark Souls when it comes to boss design and gameplay. Not so much on the world design! However, not every game needs to be a metroid-vania, so it's fine that Cuphead's world is in the same vein as 2D Mario games with an overworld you can freely travel along.

Cuphead has been in my backlog for years at this point. Now that I've taken it out, I'm baffled that it collected dust for so long. Truly one of the greatest modern video games I've played.

You can't review Cuphead without talking about the art. It's 11 out of 10. It's just off-the-scales excellent.
The gameplay is tight, the weapons are varied enough not only to lead to different play styles, but also to add replay value, the levels are intriguing and challenging (all while being fairly simplistic on paper), and it's a blast in 1 or 2 player modes.

The levels start out pretty easy, but they escalate quickly. The bosses are the old-style of bosses where you need to memorize their patterns to avoid being hit.

Lastly, the ranking system also allows for a lot of replayability as you'll want to not just beat the levels but do so more perfectly :-D

Where do I even start with Cuphead?
Lets break it down into a few parts:

1. Music
    It's no surprise that music is a talking point on why this game is so heavily favored. The jazz brings the game to life and make the player feel it in real time. Every boss, level, and map area has their own theme. For a game that has little dialogue, it sure says a lot through its music.

2. Gameplay
    The second talking point is about the gameplay more specific to the first playthrough. If your at all aware of the game, then you probably know that it is known for being exceedingly hard. And I completely agree. On the first playthrough, most bosses took me 20min-1hour past the first isle. I think this adds on to the game. Not only does it give the player something to really focus on, it feels so rewarding when the KO pops up. If you plan on buying the game, please don't rage quit. The reward is so worth the grind.

3. Scenery and Design
    I mean, what do I need to say, the game is beautiful. The 30's cartoon with the watercolor backgrounds is just amazing. The bosses, levels, and isles are extraordinary as well as things like the sounds and effects of weapons and bosses.  

Overall the game deserves its 96% positive rating, I believe it is a 10/10 and everyone should at least give it a try and beat the game at least once (on regular). I currently speedrun the game in free time and once I mastered every boss it is really relaxing to just chill through a run. Expert mode is a whole can of worms that should only be touched once you really have a grasp of every boss.

Side note: The DLC is the same experience, King's Gauntlet is pretty fun and the bosses definitely step up from the main game. I'd give the DLC an 7.5/10 but still solid.

Cutting to the chase - I personally believe this is one of the best video games ever made.

Cuphead blends a smooth & fluid control scheme with stunning 1930s animation inspired art into a flawlessly executed video game experience for me. The game is your simple classic platforming genre with a twist: Instead of journeying through the multiple linear levels in an area to fight a boss - the boss fights become the main focus with only a few of those original "Point A to Point B" style levels. This is a welcomed change - a games that are a constant wave of boss fights is becoming one of my favorite genres (Titan Souls, Shadow of the Colossus are my favorite but there are also games like Elden Ring/Bloodborne).

If your a fan of retro classic like Super Mario Bros. and shooters like contra - this is for you. You can sink a handful of hours into it at a time trying to learn boss patterns and become victorious. You can buy and upgrade weapons for a different approach - it's just wonderful. It's refreshing but somewhat nostalgic. I couldn't recommend this game higher.

My only suggestion is when you complete the game, you should be able to easily access boss fights and see their information within a menu instead of having to traverse in the over-world and walking to each level/fight. It's great for the first play-through when you discover coins, NPCs, etc. - but when I boot the game again to play more I'm just trying to get to these levels and go for  higher scores/achievements.

I like the way with secret paths to help you reach somewhere you couldn't if you were blocked by a hard boss. Some may also give you rewards. In conclusion, this game is a difficult platformer based by cartoons in the 1930s where you take on a quest with Mr. Elder Kettle. Made by an actual orchestra, which is really impressive. Games are meant to be fun. The lack of a difficulty setting is really disappointing. That makes this game inaccessible to many people. Replaying a level hundreds of times isn't my idea of fun, personally. It's a shame because I did enjoy some of the mechanics and the art is so good. Oh well.

1. Stunning Visuals: Cuphead is a visual marvel. The game's art style draws inspiration from the 1930s cartoons, featuring hand-drawn animation and character designs reminiscent of classic Disney and Fleischer Studios animations. Every frame is a work of art, and the attention to detail in replicating the era's aesthetics is simply astounding.

2. Catchy Jazz Soundtrack: The game's soundtrack, composed by Kristofer Maddigan, is a toe-tapping, jazzy masterpiece. Each level and boss battle is accompanied by a unique, period-appropriate musical score that adds to the overall charm and atmosphere of the game.

3. Challenging Gameplay: Cuphead offers a refreshing and challenging experience. The gameplay is a throwback to the old-school run-and-gun shooters of the past, with precise controls and a variety of weapons and abilities to master. Boss battles are particularly memorable, offering intense, pattern-based challenges that require skill and persistence to conquer.

4. Cooperative Multiplayer: Cuphead supports local cooperative play, allowing two players to team up and take on the game's challenges together. This cooperative mode adds another layer of enjoyment, as players work together to overcome the game's toughest obstacles.

5. Variety of Bosses: The game's boss battles are a highlight, featuring a colorful cast of quirky and memorable characters. Each boss presents a unique set of challenges and mechanics, keeping the gameplay fresh and exciting from start to finish.

6. Progression and Upgrades: Cuphead offers a sense of progression through the acquisition of new abilities and upgrades. Players can customize their playstyle by purchasing different weapons and charms, allowing for strategic choices and experimentation.

7. Respect for Tradition: Cuphead pays homage to the history of animation and gaming with great respect and attention to detail. It's a love letter to the past, and this passion is palpable in every aspect of the game.

8. Fair Difficulty Curve: Despite its reputation for being challenging, Cuphead strikes a fair difficulty balance. It's tough but not unfairly punishing, encouraging players to learn from their mistakes and gradually improve their skills.

9. Regular Updates: The developers have continued to support Cuphead with downloadable content (DLC), adding even more content and challenges to an already excellent game. This ongoing commitment to the player community is commendable.

In conclusion, Cuphead is a true gem in the world of indie gaming. Its stunning visuals, incredible soundtrack, and challenging gameplay combine to create a one-of-a-kind experience that pays homage to the golden age of animation. It's a game that not only captures the essence of retro gaming but also pushes the medium forward with its innovative artistry. Cuphead is a testament to the power of creativity and dedication in game development, and it's a must-play for anyone who appreciates the art of gaming.

In Cuphead, the player controls Cuphead, a small white man with a coffee cup for a head. It is also possible to play with two players, the second player controls Mugman; a similar character who has a coffee mug for a head. The player has infinite lives and saves items and weapons after dying. Cuphead has a gun with infinite bullets and a dash attack. As the player progresses through the game, collected gold coins can be used to purchase additional items and weapons. In each field the player must compete against a much stronger opponent who must be under fire for minutes before he is defeated. At the same time, Mugman and Cuphead can only be hit a few times by the projectiles fired at them or the game is over.

The game is great. It definetlly has bugs and sometimes unfair rng, but the gameplay is very fun and the music and animation are great. Some people say its too hard, but this difficulty makes it amazingly enjoyable to play thru.

Overall, I found Cuphead to be an incredibly enjoyable experience and highly recommend it to anyone who’s looking for a challenging time-waster.

This game is an absolute masterpiece. The music, the graphics, the difficulty, the levels and their pacing, it's hard to nit-pick. It is and will always be one of my favourite challenging games.

The only nit-pick i can find is probably to do with the shop, there are just blatantly average charms and most of the time you will go with smoke bomb, and sometimes the heart one. Weapon variation is very great though and atleast if you are completing the game on Expert, you certainly need to switch weapons quite often as the levels play very differently.

This review is based on completing the game entirely on normal and then expert difficulty before the DLC, which i have yet to play, but am very excited to! I will update this review once i have played through that also.

EDIT:

I have now completed the entirety of the DLC and i must say it just adds to the adoration i have for this game. The new powers fit in really well and the addition of Ms. Chalice adds some new mechanics and strategies. My only criticism (Which didn't bother me at all) Is that you get quite a strong sense that some of the levels were designed for Chalice, which is to say it is "normal" or harder depending on whether or not you use her for that level, which is something that wasn't able to be a problem when there were just 2 coloured cups who had the same abilities.

The bosses were also very cool and i can confirm that the DLC has just as much care put into it in literally everything, as the base game. Cuphead will always be one of my most favourite games and i give glowing recommendations to both the base game, and the DLC

Please buy this game and play it. I have gotten this game on every single platform and beaten it, it is literally my favorite game of all time. Where do I even start with Cuphead? This game has a beautiful HAND DRAWN rubber hose (1920’s cartoon) style which it nails perfectly;  The characters are all incredibly expressive, each boisterous boss is loonier than the next, with absurdly clever movesets and mind bending animations. I frequently found myself laughing at the absurdity of the bosses, some even making me pause the game because I needed a moment to process them.   Visually, this game is a 10/10. I can say the same for the soundtrack- It's literally the best soundtrack I've ever heard composed for a video game. Each boss theme adds a new layer of personality to the bosses, giving the game a much more immersive feel overall. Coupled with the game's tight controls (change your control scheme first lol) and simple yet fun mechanics, Cuphead sets you up for an unforgettable experience that no other game can or will ever even come close to. I don't mean to oversell the game with that statement, I'm trying to say that with all the hard work the devs, animators, and musicians put into the base game and DLC the game provides such a uniquely satisfying experience that I really don't think any other game out there offers. There will never be another Cuphead. I have no complaints about this game. Though it can be extremely frustrating at times it becomes an incredible experience when you master it. You KNOW it’s gonna be hard. Have some patience and give yourself enough time to learn each level. Let it fuck you long enough, and you’ll gain enough skill to dominate that shit. In other words, have sex with the game. Incredible gameplay, graphics, and some fantastic jazz music all wrapped in an incredible rubber hose asthetic. Why not give it a try? Definitely worth the 20 smackers.

Right out of the gate, the game is hard, but you already know that, what you may not know is, after a while you start to see the patterns and get faster with your combos/movements. I decided to go for a 100% (or should I say 200%?), the thing is, on my second run on expert, I felt the bosses a lot easier, except that damn robot, but after 20 attempts I managed to kill him by staying on the left on its third phase (a little tip for ya). It was a more relaxed run because I had already gone through all of them, and I knew exactly how they attack and was able to see the changes in their expert counterparts. 

But your first run is going to be hard, I'm not going to sugar coat it, so believe me when I say that it requires commitment, concentration and will. (Remember to never rage, and if you feel you are losing very often, just leave the game for a few hours and get back to it cool headed).

The game is beautiful, the style and the music are awesome, and it certainly gives the 30's vibe it was based on. So, buy it and try it, I know you will beat it, and you'll feel proud of yourself.

Cuphead calls it's difficulty 'regular'. 
It's 'regular' in the same way hair loss is 'regular' for chemo patients.

This game is harder than quitting cigarettes.
And not always fair. 

Sometimes the controls don't work right. 
And just because you've memorized a boss' patterns doesn't mean you will beat them any time soon.

Cuphead has as much balance as a toddler on a tightrope. 
and the difficulty does not scale well. Sometimes a level can be finished in one try, followed by another that takes at least an hour
 
They should fire the person who made the dragon level.
And blacklist them from game development.
and blacklist their descendants from game development, too. 

Is the game pretty? 
Definitely.
But would you sleep with someone who has herpes just because they're a 10?
If you said 'maybe', I think we're in the same boat.

I love and hate this game at the same time.
The same way I feel about some of my family members. 

The gameplay is simple, but sometimes janky.
I completely gave up on the 'parry' system.
The game may as well have told me to block bullets with a flyswatter.

Some of the upgrades are total garbage. The kind you incenerate because it isn't good enough for a trashcan. 
And maybe it has the plague in it.

I'm not convinced that anything does more than .001 damage, even the kamehameha ripoff posing as a 'super' move.
It's about as super as peter parker before the spider bite. 

I pray that an asteroid hits the earth so I don't have to suffer through any more of this mess.
I can't quit. This game is addictive. 

Every time I finish a level, I feel a slight sense of satisfaction, followed by abysmal dread. Because I know I have to fight some other monstrosity from a prohibition-era cartoon.

Get ready to be stomped on by everything from sunflowers to candy corns to the devil himself.

I recommend you take beta blockers before each session to keep your heart rate under control.
If you're a recovering/recovered addict, this game may induce sudden urges to relapse.

You have been warned, and good luck.

I'm gonna beat it. 
I'm gonna win. 
Because this is America.
And I smash cups when I get angry.

EDIT: Several years later. Finally beat the devil.

Well, Cumhead and his pal Thugman, they like to roll the dice
By chance they came 'pon Devil's game and, gosh, they paid the price, paid the price
And now they're fighting for their cocks on a mission fraught with dread
And if they proceed but don't succeed, well... The devil will take their tips

Cuphead evokes that rare, yet sought-after feeling of furious joy and fuels the "one more time" feeling.
However, if you're not interested in tricky gameplay, don't let the captivating art style fool you. After dying countless times, I can safely say that I thoroughly enjoyed my time with Cuphead.

The game also works perfectly on a steam deck: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GSn7XxYqcCs

It will not escape anyone's attention that Cuphead as a game throws itself over a somewhat unusual tack.
The bleed-through of colors on the screen, the crackle of an imaginary vinyl record, the standard controller controls that are compatible in every era.
Skillful thought has gone into giving everything as nostalgic a twist as possible.
Over the course of the game, you will unlock different types of weapons, such as a weak but auto-seeking shot or a short but strong shot.
In addition, you also unlock certain items that give you small advantages, such as an extra heart or a faster charging super meter.
Cuphead has a parry move that lets you hit anything pink without getting hit yourself, plus your supermove meter grows faster.
You can also unlock various super moves, such as a fighting spirit of your own.

In addition to a solo adventure, Cuphead can also be played with a friend. One then plays as Cuphead and the other as Mugman.
This gameplay is fun but it does come with some problems. If the two are not roughly on the same level it can be a lot of frustration for the weaker player, but you also have this with super mario co op game sessions of course.
It always has to be saved or you have to wait for it, but it's about teamwork, isn't it?

Cuphead is a pleasure for the eyes and ears and the game is full of challenge. It is for a very specific target group, namely go-getters. The smallest mistakes can be punished harshly and this can be very discouraging. However, for players who don't give up after a few failures, the gameplay is excellent.

Oh, where do I even begin with the absolute marvel that is Cuphead? Strap yourselves in, fellow gamers, because this game is a rollercoaster of joy that will have your heart pounding with excitement from start to finish!

Let's talk about that jaw-dropping hand-drawn artstyle that's a pure masterpiece in itself. Cuphead transports you into a whimsical world straight out of a 1930s cartoon, with characters and environments that burst with life and charm. Every frame is meticulously crafted, oozing with personality and paying homage to the golden era of animation. It's like playing through a living, breathing work of art – a true testament to the love and dedication poured into every single pixel.

But hold onto your seats, because the gameplay will knock your socks off! The level of creativity and variety in Cuphead's boss battles and run-and-gun stages is nothing short of mind-boggling. From dancing flowers to ginormous zeppelins, each encounter feels like a unique and exhilarating challenge. The adrenaline rush as you dodge, jump, and shoot your way through waves of colorful chaos is pure gaming ecstasy. And don't even get me started on the upgrades and power-ups – they're like the sprinkles on top of an already delicious cupcake!

And speaking of love, it's abundantly clear that the developers poured their hearts and souls into making Cuphead a labor of love. The attention to detail in every aspect of the game, from the subtle animations to the witty dialogue, is astounding. You can practically feel the passion and dedication radiating off the screen. It's as if they took all the fond memories of their own gaming experiences and combined them into a single, perfect package for us to enjoy.

But the love doesn't stop there – the soundtrack is an auditory delight that will have you humming along even after you've put down the controller. The jazzy, toe-tapping tunes perfectly complement the zany visuals, creating an immersive experience that's a feast for both the eyes and ears.

In conclusion, Cuphead isn't just a game – it's a work of art, a love letter to gaming history, and a testament to the power of passion and creativity. The hand-drawn artstyle, the heart-pounding gameplay, and the sheer dedication poured into every facet of the game make it an absolute gem that deserves a place in every gamer's collection. So don't just play Cuphead – savor it, cherish it, and get ready for a gaming journey like no other!

Cuphead made me feel more good and more bad than any other game I’ve played in the last several years. I swore, laughed, and hollered with delight. I hated it (and my own fingers) for long stretches but, having finished, I realise that’s more or less the point – I emerged from all that pain smiling. Rather than simply offering the player what they want, Cuphead makes them earn that right – the rewards, if you can hack the tests, are absolutely worth it. 

Cuphead is incredible for more than just its looks. But before you dive in, make sure you actually want a game that plays like this, and not just a game that looks like this.
