Cuphead é um jogo indie estilo anos 30  onde vc é o Xicrinho(Cuphead) ou o Caneco(Mugman) e vc deve sua alma pro diabo, mas para se livrar disso vc pode trabalhar de agiota pra ele, assim vc pega os contratos de outros devedores e batalha com eles pra pegar o contrato, dependendo do ponto de vista da história, fica mt engraçado KKKKKKK. Eu recomendo esse jogo, vale a pena o dinheiro, e se vc tiver uma net boa, da pra jogar de dois sem seu amigo pagar (de longe msm, chama remote play) recomendo tmb usar um controle pq facilita e deixa a experiência melhor,
Cuphead é com certeza um jogo q vai mudar sua vida e é mt bom, joguem (recomendo pegar uma promo boa).

Be aware!

It all starts pretty harmless. You'll just start the game and will get your a$$ handed to you the first couple tries. Then you'll learn the ropes and get better. You'll feel kinda comfy around and think "it is not THAT bad".

And that's where you are the most vulnerable. You got confident and now you start with thoughts like "maybe I can finish everything A rank on this isle before I move on". You will do that. And then you'll even get your first P on a run and gun.

Congratulations! You fell for the trap. NOW the real pain and your eternal suffering will begin. You will forever be in pain trying to get those A, S and P ranks. And then you begin with challenge runs. You will raaaage a lot. Your life is over, your soul is not yours anymore and the devil won once again.

10/10 would sell my soul again.

Cuphead is a game that stands out in the world of indie gaming, combining beautiful artistic design with an unexpectectly challenging gameplay experience. It's a unique blend of old-school run-and-gun action, a 1930s cartoon aesthetic, and an adrenaline-pumping sense of difficulty.

One of the first things that strike you about Cuphead is its visuals. The game is an absolute work of art, paying homage to the classic cartoons of the 1930s like Betty Boop and Mickey Mouse. Every frame is hand-drawn and meticulously animated, creating an immersive and nostalgic atmosphere. The dedication to this style is remarkable and sets Cuphead apart as a visual masterpiece in the gaming world.

However, Cuphead isn't just about looks; it's also about challenging gameplay. From the moment you start, you'll be thrust into a series of increasingly difficult boss battles and platforming levels. The game doesn't hold your hand, and you'll likely die countless times as you learn boss patterns and level layouts. This level of difficulty can be polarizing; some players revel in the challenge, while others might find it frustrating.

The controls in Cuphead are tight and responsive, which is crucial given the precision required to conquer its many challenges. The game encourages experimentation, as you can choose different weapons and abilities to suit your playstyle. This adds depth to the gameplay and ensures that no two players will have the same experience.

The soundtrack in Cuphead is another standout feature. The jazzy tunes perfectly complement the 1930s theme and add an extra layer of immersion to the experience. It's clear that every aspect of this game was crafted with love and attention to detail.

While Cuphead's difficulty can be a bit overwhelming, it's important to note that it's not insurmountable. Each defeat feels like a learning experience, and the sense of accomplishment when you finally conquer a challenging boss is incredibly rewarding. The game's pacing, with its variety of boss battles and platforming levels, keeps things fresh and engaging throughout.

In conclusion, Cuphead is a gaming gem that's as beautiful as it is challenging. If you appreciate hand-drawn art, classic animation, and a stiff but fair challenge, it's a must-play. However, if you're easily frustrated by tough games, it might not be your cup of tea. Regardless, Cuphead is an artistic triumph that will be remembered as a unique and innovative entry in the world of video games.

You know you've reached a new level of gaming when you start dreaming in 1930s cartoons and dodge bullets while sipping your morning coffee. Cuphead has redefined my breakfast routine, turning my cup into a survival tool and saucers into deadly frisbees. Just yesterday, I tried to parry a flying insect thinking it was a pink coin. The game's so charmingly ruthless that I now negotiate with my boss using only platforming moves. "Listen, boss, I'll jump over this pile of paperwork and parry your unreasonable demands – deal?"

Who needs caffeine-induced jitters when you can have the Cuphead-induced shakes? It's like an adrenaline-pumping dance recital with bosses who've overdosed on espresso, and you're their partner with two left feet. My reflexes are sharper than ever, but my mug collection has never been so shattered. And don't even get me started on the soundtrack – it's like Louis Armstrong and a kazoo had a lovechild, and that child learned to play jazz on a xylophone made of cartoon anvils.

If you're up for a challenge that makes skydiving into a pit of crocodiles sound reasonable, then grab your favorite beverage (probably in a plastic cup for safety) and jump into Cuphead. It's the only game that makes a teacup's quest for justice so ridiculously, frustratingly, and fantastically entertaining. Just remember, if your coffee starts whispering strategies to you, it might be time for a break.

Oh, my stars and garters, let me tell you about that there Cuphead game. Now, don't let this old grandma's lack of gaming skills fool you – Cuphead's got a grip on my heart like no other. It's like trying to knit a sweater blindfolded, but with each stitch, I'm weaving a tale of determination and dreams.

From the moment those jazzy tunes start playing, I'm whisked into a world that's part cartoon, part carnival, and all sorts of devilishly difficult. Those bosses! Whew, they've given me more gray hairs than my grandkids ever did. But there's something about the challenge that keeps me coming back, like trying to catch fireflies on a summer night.

My fingers fumble on the controller, and I'm not quite sure what all those fancy moves are supposed to do, but there's hope in every misstep. I'm like a grandma determined to bake a perfect pie, even if it takes me till the cows come home. Every time I manage to land a hit on one of them ornery bosses, I feel like I've won the county fair pie-baking contest!

Now, I may not have mastered this Cuphead business just yet, but mark my words, one day this old gal is gonna dance through those levels like nobody's business. I'll dodge those projectiles with the grace of a waltzing couple, and I'll give those bosses a run for their money. And when that day comes, you can bet your bottom dollar, I'll be the proudest grandma in the gaming world.

So, my dearies, if you're looking for a game that'll test your patience and tickle your determination, give Cuphead a whirl. It's a bit like knitting a scarf with three hands, but oh, the stories you'll tell when you finally unravel the mystery of that devilish challenge!

Rating: ★★★★★

A fantastic game that adapts old cartoon style art design, excellent music, and episode and boss designs.

The game is quite challenging, and that's what makes it good. Every boss you defeat gives you a sense of satisfaction and accomplishment. I can't say the story is great, but it serves the purpose of this style of game. It was truly a unique experience, even though it can get on your nerves at times, you feel good when you discover the weaknesses of the enemies and defeat them using this knowledge.

In the game, the bosses' health increases when you play with two people, but despite this, we played this game with two people and had a lot of fun... A five-star game.

And by the way, the story of the developers quitting their jobs, going into debt to make this game is a great example reminding us to pursue our passion and that we only have one opportunity to live life and to do what we really want to do.

Would you like to spend several hours dying to the same boss over and over again, constantly get hit by obstacles which shouldn't hit, and rinse and repeat the process 19 times in base game or 26 with DLC included? Well my friend, you've come to the right place! Cuphead! Play as Cuphead and/or Mugman, along with Miss Chalice as DLC as you scrawl across several worlds, with each world hiding secrets and being harder than the last world. Brave through mausoleums where Miss Chalice is trapped in, and free her in order for you to unlock new ultimates. Unlock several different shots and perks using gold coins, each with their own benefits and drawbacks. Find secret hidden paths on the maps which help you get further into the area, only for you to backtrack due to the fact that you need all the bosses' soul contract. Still not enough content? Get the delicious last course for more awesome content!

I am a 45 yo father, probably one of the oldest people playing this game. I am a single father to my Son, who is 14 now. My son got this game for Christmas in 2021 from his uncle, so we installed it on his computer and he started playing. By the end of the week he had 24 hours on this game. This was horrible for me, as it was already hard for me to find ways to spend time with my son, as he is always out with his friends or just watching YouTube. I loved it as it was the best time I had spent with my Son since my wife had died. This game has ever since brought me and my son closer again and now we actually spend time together outside the house together as well. This game reminded me that there's fun to be had in everything, and it has brought both me and my Son many happy memories

Well, I put off buying this one for years because while the game is beautiful, I was wary that an ultra-hard boss rush platform shooter wasn't for me - but that wasn't the case at all. I'm so glad that I finally buckled down and bought this game (along with the DLC - which really is essential especially since it's so cheap). 

Cuphead is probably everything you've heard - a gorgeous action-platformer that is uncompromising when it comes to difficulty, but it absolutely got its hooks in me and wouldn't let go. Beating the game for the first time is satisfying, but where I didn't expect to go was getting an S-rank on all the bosses. This is totally optional, and you have to beat the bosses on expert mode to get these S-ranks, but there have been few gaming experiences that I've had that have been as satisfying. This became the only game I really wanted to play as I moved every closer to getting a perfect rank against the bosses and levels. It can be extremely frustrating at times (like all difficult games) but the game is just so flat out fun and satisfying to play that I couldn't put it down.

I would highly recommend this game even if it wasn't one of the best-looking games ever made due to it's immaculate controls that only get more and more familiar and feel better the more you play and it's incredible design. However, along with all of that, it does happen to be one of the best looking (and sounding) games ever made due to the incredible 1930's aesthetic.

Both on the surface and underneath, Cuphead is an absolute masterpiece of a video game.

Title: Cuphead - A Hand-Drawn Masterpiece of Challenging Fun!

Rating: ★★★★★ (5/5)

Review:

Cuphead is an extraordinary and visually stunning run-and-gun game that pays homage to classic 1930s cartoons while delivering an incredibly challenging and rewarding experience. Developed by Studio MDHR, this indie gem has enchanted players with its unique art style, addictive gameplay, and memorable characters.

From the moment I entered the whimsical world of Cuphead, I was mesmerized by its hand-drawn animation, vibrant colors, and jazzy soundtrack that transport players back to the golden age of animation. The painstaking attention to detail in every frame showcases the immense love and dedication poured into this labor of love.

The core gameplay of Cuphead revolves around intense boss battles and run-and-gun levels, each offering a distinctive and imaginative design. With a variety of unique bosses, each with their own set of challenging patterns and attacks, every encounter is a thrilling test of skill and reflexes. Learning the attack patterns and mastering the timing is immensely satisfying, turning each boss defeat into a triumph of perseverance.

Cuphead's challenging difficulty level is one of its standout features. While it can be punishing at times, the game never feels unfair. The sense of accomplishment that comes from overcoming seemingly insurmountable odds is unparalleled, making it an incredibly gratifying experience for players seeking a genuine challenge.

The game's co-op mode allows players to team up with a friend, adding an extra layer of fun and camaraderie. Playing with a friend can make the game feel less daunting while still presenting a formidable challenge that requires teamwork and coordination.

Moreover, Cuphead's unique world map and branching paths add a sense of exploration and non-linearity to the gameplay. This feature encourages players to revisit levels, discover secrets, and unlock hidden content, extending the game's replay value.

While Cuphead is an exceptional gaming experience, it may not be everyone's cup of tea due to its high difficulty level. Players looking for a more relaxed and casual experience might find the intense challenge to be overwhelming.

In conclusion, Cuphead is an absolute masterpiece that pushes the boundaries of what an indie game can achieve. Its hand-drawn animation, delightful characters, and challenging gameplay make it a must-play for any gaming enthusiast. If you're ready for a visually striking and adrenaline-pumping adventure, Cuphead is waiting to test your skills and deliver an unforgettable journey into the world of classic cartoons and unforgiving fun!

*Immediately sell their soul to the devil*[/b]
[i]-The entire plot[/i]
[hr][/hr]

[b]Cuphead[/b], from a bygone era a very simple action game that spots incredible rubber-hose style animation inspired by the very fist cartoons to great effect, a smooth animation galore where also design was adapted to make it all work.

[h1]Gameplay[/h1]
As I said, from a gameplay perspective the game is simple, that isn’t to say it’s easy.
A run and gun game more focused on boss battles, it leaves some room for costumization with projectile patterns and special abilities but stays simple enough to not overwhelm the player with useless menus and builds for a game that has to be felt rather than calculated.

[h1]X-Factor[/h1]
Amazing animations from the olden days of Disney applied to great designed characters and enemies, it also doubles to clearly foreshadow the various kinds of attacks that will require you to either be quick on your fees or know where to stand to avoid them, sometimes both on some stages however, you might get hit through sheer bad luck because either something appeared to the side of the screen or projectiles lining up in a way to cut any chance to continue unscathed.

[h1]Story[/h1]
The story is simplistic, the titular cuphead blinded by greed makes a pact with the devil, and now has to collect souls in his place if he wants himself out of the contract.  

[h1]Downsides[/h1]
Some bosses get frustrating, and especially walking stages where bullets can spawn from the sides of the screen without warning for a cheap shot
[hr][/hr]

But that’s all for the criticism, a simple game with a lovely style.
A modern “blast from the past” if that’s even a thing.

This game is like a grilled cheese on a plastic plate, delicious. cuphead is a platformer where you fight off against monsters as a cup of milk. You defeat these monsters with finger guns. You can shoot them all you want until they are dead like a vine meme. Now me personally, i really enjoy cuphead, its always good to have a challenge every once in a while. Now lets discuss how cuphead is good. We get our bowl of milk, then we add the first ingredient, the characters. Some could be better but most are great. Next we add the art style... PERFECTION. Then we add the bosses, they are all great. Now finally, we add the delicous last course. Its a really good expansion for a game where you fight with a cup and a mug. So in conclusion, This game is amazing and a perfect challenge for you. So have fun playing cuphead if you are going to buy it.

DISCLAIMER: I do not own The Delicious Last Course at this time. The review that follows is about the base game.\

SUMMARY

Never before have I had such a good time playing a game that I wanted to throw against a brick wall. Cuphead is a delight, with fantastic visuals, fun sounds, and a grueling gameplay loop that manages to just barely avoid being too frustrating to play. The reward for pushing through this game's persistent difficulty? Immense satisfaction, delivered through deft maneuvers and well-timed jumps that the game teaches via trial by hellfire. Let's do a pro/con/neutrality list, shall we?

PROS:

Cuphead aimed to capture the rubberhose feel of early cartoons, and in this attempt, Studio MDHR knocked it out of the park. From little quirks inherent to older-style humor to the old-timey sound, this game is a work of art even beyond the beautiful hand-drawn animation this game plays in. It's a stylistic choice that really paid off.

The controls are precise, which has been as much a boon to me as it has a bane. This game punishes misinputs really hard, but, at least in my case, I was only really upset at my own skill issue.

The bosses are tough as nails, but fair. It often feels like perhaps they might not be, since some of their attacks are not easily anticipated at first, but the game is trying to teach you to keep going no matter how hard it gets. Every attack from a boss that would be a problem is well-telegraphed or slow-moving.

The multiplayer aspect feels well-balanced. I don't have much else to say about it.

The level design of the run 'n gun levels tends to be visually interesting, despite their scenes remaining relatively the same throughout.

Gosh, the character design. I loved just about every one of them, with enough exceptions that I didn't really mind what didn't sit well with me.

CONS:

More of a nitpick, but the run 'n gun levels don't really have that well-telegraphed feel, in my opinion. Granted, they are outnumbered by quite a bit by the bosses, and you can always do another run, but I have generally felt more frustrated by sudden projectiles or gaps from these platforming sections than anything the bosses through. They are still solid levels, so I feel this barely counts as a con, but let's list it anyway.

OVERALL:

Cuphead is a fantastic experience that fans of cartoons, hardcore gamers, and more cooperative sorts should definitely try. It's hard in all the right ways, thematic, and simply a delight to behold. Bravo, MDHR, bravo!

Cuphead is an absolutely amazing game. The art is amazing, especially considered that its supposed to be based off of 1930s art which I thought I wouldn't like as much as other modern games' art, but its definitely one of my favorite styles. As soon as I played the first level I knew I would love this game. The bosses are super fun, and the art, sounds and gameplay are all EXTREMELY satisfying. The movement is kind of like hollow knight (the dash, and the snappy, responsive movement.) which is a movement system that I think should be in every 2D platformer. It's pretty challenging, but I'm not sure if I accidentally enabled a "hard mode" option or something, since when I completed the first run & gun level for the second time, it changed my health to three instead of six. I think if I hadn't played the level for a second time, my health would have stayed at six, but its possibly on purpose. I'm not done yet, but so far this game is amazing. Definitely would recommend.

It has been years since I played this game, and i admit, I probably should have written this review sooner.

The visuals are undeniably beautiful, and the music is also stellar. Unfortunately, this is the only good thing I can say about it.

For those of you who haven't yet heard, this game is hard. Unreasonably so. And no, I don't consider that a good thing.

Some will respond by simply saying "get good." Well, I did. I played the game, faced it's challenges, and even beat the final boss. And I hated every moment of it, so you're going to need a better counter to my argument.

As I went through the game, driven by bitter resentment, determined to prove I can beat a game and STILL hate it for being difficult, I couldn't help but nitpick every minor detail, looking for more reasons to hate it.

In hindsight, I may have been a bit harsh. But I will still stand by my opinion. This game is grossly overrated at best.

If you are like me, if you don't find joy in excessive difficulty, if you actively hate the phrase "get good" and all who have utterd it. Then STAY AWAY from Cuphead!

If all you want is to experience the old school cartoon style, I genuinely recommend that you go to YouTube and watch someone else play it. Otherwise you might get so sick of the art style that you contemplate building a time machine to go back in time and strangle Walt Disney like I have.

After beating the game I swore to never touch it again, I have no reason to. I won't play the dlc, nor will I play any sequels that might come out.

I only regret not buying a physical copy of the game so I can physically bury it in a ditch where it belongs.

Cuphead is an absolute gem of a game that not only pays homage to the golden age of animation but also delivers an exhilarating and challenging gameplay experience. From the moment I laid eyes on its hand-drawn visuals, I was really intrigued by its unique and stunning art style.Especially since it's the first of it's kind I've personally ever seen. It's like stepping into a living, breathing cartoon world, where every frame feels carefully crafted with love and care. And despite my relatively low playtime of 15 hours I enjoyed it all the way through. And I'm excited to try out the DLC and possibly update my review to include it too.

But don't be fooled by its charming appearance; Cuphead offers a tough ass challenge that demands precise timing, lightning-fast reflexes, and strategic thinking. Each boss battle is a light show, testing your skills and pushing you to your limits. And while the difficulty may seem intimidating at first, the immense satisfaction that comes from overcoming each hurdle is unlike any other.

One aspect that truly stands out is the game's unique and beautiful soundtrack. The jazzy tunes perfectly complement the frantic action, further immersing you in the 1930's era. Every track is catchy, lively, and expertly composed, enhancing the overall experience and adding an extra layer of enjoyment to the gameplay.

The attention to detail in Cuphead is astounding. From the wacky character designs to the imaginative boss encounters, it's evident that studio poured their hearts into creating this artwork of a game. The game is a true labor of love, and it shines through in every aspect, making it an unforgettable journey from start to finish.

I also really enjoy the idea of being able to work together locally to beat bosses as not only does it allow for room for replayability but it also gives you a new way of fighting bosses and new strategies depending on who you play it with and how you go about it. Fighting the same boss is a different experience on your own than with a friend. Definitely a top tier game for me and I can't wait to try out the DLC. I'm sure i'll like it just as much.

Cuphead, developed by StudioMDHR, is an incredibly challenging and visually stunning run-and-gun game that pays homage to the golden age of animation. As someone who initially struggled to conquer its formidable difficulty but eventually triumphed over every boss and collected every achievement on Steam, I can confidently say that Cuphead is a masterclass in perseverance and rewarding gameplay.

The first thing that strikes you about Cuphead is its breathtaking art style. The game beautifully captures the hand-drawn, 1930s cartoon aesthetic, with its vibrant colors, fluid animations, and imaginative character designs. Every frame is a visual feast, bringing to life a world filled with zany characters, imaginative landscapes, and a delightful sense of nostalgia. The meticulous attention to detail is evident in every aspect, from the smoothness of the animations to the lovingly crafted backgrounds. Cuphead's visuals are truly a work of art and create an immersive experience that feels like stepping into a classic animated film.

However, beneath its charming exterior lies an immense challenge. Cuphead is notorious for its difficulty, demanding precision, quick reflexes, and strategic thinking from players. The game is a series of exhilarating boss battles and intense platforming sections, each requiring careful observation and mastery of its mechanics. From the outset, Cuphead can be incredibly punishing, with each defeat feeling like a setback. Yet, it is precisely this difficulty that makes each victory all the more satisfying.

Cuphead's controls are tight and responsive, allowing for precise movement and the execution of intricate maneuvers. As you progress and become more adept, you start to uncover the game's depth, discovering new strategies and techniques to overcome each encounter. The learning curve is steep, but the sense of progression and growth as you become more skilled is incredibly rewarding. Overcoming the seemingly insurmountable challenges becomes a testament to your dedication, patience, and perseverance.

The boss battles in Cuphead are the highlight of the game. Each boss is unique, with their own distinct patterns and attacks to learn and counter. The variety of bosses ensures that every encounter feels fresh and exciting, keeping you on your toes throughout the entire adventure. Each victory feels hard-earned, and the rush of adrenaline as you finally overcome a particularly challenging boss is unparalleled.

Beyond its difficulty, Cuphead also offers a fantastic soundtrack that perfectly complements the on-screen action. The jazz-infused tunes are catchy, energetic, and add an extra layer of immersion to the game. The sound design, too, is top-notch, with each hit, jump, and explosion fitting seamlessly into the overall audiovisual experience.

While Cuphead's difficulty can be seen as its greatest strength, it can also be a double-edged sword. Some players may find the relentless challenge frustrating and may feel discouraged at times. However, the satisfaction of conquering each obstacle far outweighs the initial frustration. It's a game that rewards determination and persistence, and it's a testament to the developers' commitment to delivering a truly memorable gaming experience.

In conclusion, Cuphead is a remarkable game that marries stunning visuals, challenging gameplay, and an unforgettable atmosphere. As someone who initially struggled but eventually conquered its demanding nature, I can attest to the immense satisfaction of mastering each encounter and achieving every achievement on Steam. Cuphead stands as a testament to the joy of overcoming adversity and showcases the beauty of persistence in the face of daunting challenges. If you are up for a thrilling and visually mesmerizing adventure that will put your skills to the test, Cuphead is an absolute must-play title that will leave you with a profound sense of accomplishment.

Cuphead is a game that took me on a rollercoaster of emotions. I was both delighted and frustrated, laughing and swearing all at once. But in the end, I found immense joy in the challenge it presented. Visually, it's an absolute stunner, with its 1930s animation style and hand-drawn characters. The music perfectly complements the action, immersing me in the game's surreal world. However, let's not forget that Cuphead is insanely difficult. It's unforgiving, with no checkpoints and no way to regain health. The boss battles are intense and require precision and pattern memorization. The game's structure is linear, divided into worlds and levels, with each boss encounter bringing its own unique twist. The randomization of certain elements can sometimes feel unfair, but it adds a layer of unpredictability. Despite the challenges, every victory felt incredibly rewarding, making me feel like a better player. Cuphead is not just a visually stunning game; it's a test of skill and determination. Just be prepared for a tough ride if you decide to take on this beautifully frustrating adventure.

I am a 55 year old biker and trucker father, and probably one of the oldest people playing this game. I am a single father to my Son, who is 15 now. My son got this game for from his uncle, so we installed it on his computer and he started playing. By the end of the week he had 12 hours on this game. This was horrible for me, as it was already hard for me to find ways to spend time with my son, as he is always out with his friends or just watching YouTube. So i decided to make a Steam account and get this game to see if I could maybe play alongside him. I loaded into the game and started playing but I was stuck on what you where supposed to do. I asked my Son for help and he let me borrow his controller. Me and my son then played in turns and I loved it as it was the best time I had spent with my Son since my wife had died. This game has ever since brought me and my son closer again and now we actually spend time together outside the house together as well. This game reminded me that there's fun to be had in everything, and it has brought both me and my son many happy memories.

What you see in the trailer is exactly what you get. The traditional rubber hose animation style is all authentically replicated, the soundtrack perfectly captures the big band jazz feel, and there are plenty of cultural references to the 1900s. This game is authentic across the board. It's certainly not easy, but the game's charming and consistent atmosphere keeps you locked in, whether it be while you're facing against any of the several boss-type enemies or the few run 'n' gun levels. The difficulty may not be for everyone, but it's definitely a well-made game.

I first knew this game through Friday Night Funkin': Indie Cross (one of best FNF community mod). You must try that game though, but keep it aside now and lets review this game right now.

The art and animation are real feast for the eyes and keep better and better. Everything about it - from character design to environment design - is truly impressive. I love all of them.  The story is pretty straightforward: based on the game's description, you play as a debt collector for soul contracts to repay your own gambling debts. Nothing exceptional here.

The gameplay? It's brutal and humbling. This was the first game that made me realize my dodging skills while attacking enemies is pretty sucks especially on normal mode. Honestly, I had to opt for the easier levels to finish this game. However, it's still entertaining and  keep things fresh throughout all the levels and boss fights. Speaking of bosses, their unique mechanics are particularly notable - I absolutely loved them.

The soundtrack is quite good too. While I'm not exactly a jazz fan, I found myself enjoying every second of music while playing this game.

In conclusion, I would recommend Cuphead to anyone who enjoys cooperative and casual gameplay, without much focus on the storyline. If you're looking for an immersive story, you might want to give this one a pass since it's not the selling point of this game. But in terms of art, gameplay, and music, it's definitely worth a shot!

The game itself is very hard and sometimes it can make you rage, but the feeling of beating a boss you've been struggling with is amazing. Playing this does not require a good PC (I always get 60 fps). Most importantly the music and graphics of this game are incredible. The old-timey drawings have been made with a pencil and ink on paper, and then colors in Photoshop, and the soundtrack was played live musician and it's so good I have it on my Spotify playlist. I give it a straight 10/10!

Six years prior, I set aside this game, stymied by a seemingly insurmountable Dragon Boss. Yet, with the passage of time and growth in my gaming acumen, I felt inspired to revisit this challenge. Half a dozen years later, I have not only confronted this game, but have also truly savored the experience. Reflecting on it, the endeavor was not as daunting as I originally perceived.

Without hesitation, I endorse this game for its remarkable combination of art direction, audio design, and a captivating soundtrack. The challenges it presents, especially with its bosses and intense 'run and gun' stages, are tough but predominantly equitable. These elements, along with others, have given me an unforgettable journey, a testament to the game's excellence.

Moreover, the experience has been particularly enjoyable when played on the Steam Deck. So, to all gamers looking for a finely balanced challenge coupled with a feast for the senses, I couldn't recommend this game more.

When I was a kid, I used to watch cartoons on a daily basis. Everyday when I come home from school, I turn on the television and head straight to Cartoon Network, Nickelodeon, or any other family-friendly channel airing cartoons at the time of my viewing. Do keep in mind that this was in the early 2000s, which were, in my opinion, the "golden age of cartoons," with classic after classic being produced constantly. Each and every channel is an accumulation of its own magnum opus, laying the foundation of what they represent as family-friendly channels with visions to inspire and, most importantly, entertain the youth with joy and laughter. Cartoons like Spongebob Squarepants, The Grim Adventures of Billy and Mandy, and Hey Arnold, to name a few, helped me get through tough times at school and inspired me to be a happier person. I like to think of them as filters of joy. Every time I get home from school feeling stressed and overwhelmed, watching cartoons can instantly turn all that around. It was truly one of the most memorable times of my life, and I am eternally grateful to the studios that took the time to contribute to many people's childhoods, including mine.

Flash forward to 2017, a game called Cuphead was released. The first time I saw the gameplays on streaming platforms, it instantly transported me back to the early 2000s.I suddenly remember the good times that I had while watching cartoons. I felt like Ego when he first tasted Ratatouille. Although the game was not inspired by the cartoons of my time, I still feel like this game was a sincere love letter to all the people who grew up with cartoons. Each era had its own unique cartoons to look forward to, but they all shared the same vision: to spread the word of joy and laughter for children all across the world. I was not in a favorable position in life before this game came out, but when it did, I was again reminded to become the joyful person I once was. The game reminded me what to cling onto when things get awry. Although I am still struggling, at least I now know that you can always cling onto something, even the smallest of things. So thank you, Studio MDHR; you guys are legends!

That being said, don't play this fucking game. This game is as evil as the words coming out of the mouths of your asian mom's siblings at a family reunion. I fucking warned y'all.

Incredible art style with beautiful, hand drawn animation based off of 1930s cartoons. But this game isn't just style over substance, this game delivers from the gameplay side as well. The game has really unique, fun boss fights in 3 worlds (or 4 with DLC). The game is frustratingly difficult sometimes but when you finally beat the hell out of the boss that was troubling you it feels incredible. The only complaint I have is that the Run 'n' Gun Levels kinda suck and with Run 'n' Gun being the only way to get coins in the main game it's not the best. This minor complaint was addressed with the DLC as it adds extremely fun, parry based bosses that give you coins. Either way this game is an absolute masterpiece and an absolute must play. 9.5/10
